    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "658875f297dd8b2e",
      "text": "This theory is relatively new. It was developed in the 1940s on the basis of technical considerations as to how systems, system states and also outputs of systems could be kept stable under variable environmental conditions. The answer to this question lay in the well-known feedback model, i.e. in the idea that there was an apparatus which could measure certain distances, i.e. information from the environment, in relation to a desirable system state and switch on or switch off the mechanics of the system depending on whether the distance provided satisfactory or unsatisfactory measured values. You know this from the example of the thermostat; in the literature this example is also always given as a \"paradigm\" in the original sense, that is, as an example, as a prototype. But there were many other tasks in the 1940s that people tried to solve with corresponding models, not least in war technology, for example. Whereas in the past, when you had to shoot at aircraft with anti-aircraft guns, you had to deal with a mechanical device, with a ring through which you had to look and orient the guns, depending on how you had to hold forward and so on, this was now automated so that the distance could be measured and converted in each case and you could increase the accuracy independently of the gunner's eye. This was one of the tasks at that time. However, it was immediately recognized that there was a general principle underlying this, which is also used in biology, for example, when it is a question of keeping the blood temperature or the sugar content of the blood constant. So there are devices that are not constantly in operation, but only come into operation when certain defects, certain distances, certain differences assume a value that is too large."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "b0544b15f5e3a21c",
      "text": "So why is this model so significant? First of all, it is generalizable. That is one point. The attraction was to keep trying it out in new areas. Second, it was possible to believe that in this way one could reformulate the old teleology, that is, the old theory of purpose. With teleology, one had had in the old European framework the idea that there are certain purposes which attract causal processes, which thus enter into the process as cause itself, although they are future states. This had already been abandoned in the early modern period and replaced by mental causes, that is, it was now imagined that purposes are current, present conceptions of future states conditioned by past experiences, and that these conceptions, because they are now already there, can mechanically trigger certain motor activities. In the ductus of this, if you will, mechanization of teleological causalities, cybernetics was now able to explain somewhat more precisely than before how it is possible or what apparatures are presupposed if one wants to keep certain system states stable. The hope was not only directed to generalization per se, but also to the reconstruction of a classical stream of thought with modern, let us say, technical means. Finally, that was the reason for the name, control ideas were added. Cybernetes is the helmsman of a ship, and one could well imagine that if one wants to keep a ship on a straight course, one has to correct the conditions of wind and waves, i.e. counter-steer or re-steer if necessary, in order to keep the course. Cybernetes is the helmsman, and cybernetics is the science of the art of steering technical, perhaps also psychological, in any case also social systems."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "484a5c117de35ecc",
      "text": "That was the idea. It is strange that from this idea the concept of control, social guidance, steering and so on has remained and has led again and again to the illusion that one can control a system with cybernetic techniques or perhaps also with other means thought of today rather in terms of action theory. But what exactly does \"control\" mean in this cybernetic context? It does not mean that the future state of the system can be determined in all concrete details or even only in the broad and general, in the essential features, if one wants to express it in old European terms, so that one can already say now what the system will look like in the future. Instead, it is really only a matter of not allowing certain differences to become too great or of reducing them. It's about reducing deviations from the target course, deviations from the desired state, deviations from a certain temperature at which you want to keep the house, and so on. And if you can keep the temperature in the house constant, that doesn't mean that no burglars will come, that the furniture will stay in the house, that the carpets won't be ruined, or that the electricity will work in the kitchen. So cybernetics at first always refers only to specific instances, specific differences. One has to invent a very complicated system of multivariable control mechanisms and even of the control of control mechanisms, i.e. the networking of cybernetic circuits, if one wants to get somewhat in the direction that one can foresee in which state a system will be in the future.\n"
    },
