      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "15747de21cce4562",
      "text": "JAHRAUS, Oliver, NASSEHI, Armin, GRIZELJ, Mario, SAAKE, Irmhild, KIRCHMEIER, Christian and MÜLLER, Julian (eds.), 2012. Luhmann-Handbuch: Leben – Werk – Wirkung. Stuttgart: Verlag J.B. Metzler. ISBN 978-3-476-02368-1."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "ed119e10e01ae561",
      "text": "The transition from first-order cybernetics to second-order cybernetics becomes visible in the now famous thermostat example. Second-order cybernetics argues that here the controlled (heater) and the controller (thermostat) control each other reciprocally and that through this reciprocal control the clear distinction between controller and controlled becomes impossible. The clear distinction is replaced by a \"control of control\" (Esposito 2005, 295). In the final analysis, this means that both the establishment and deconstruction of the controlled/controller distinction are attributional phenomena. An observer observes a behavior and then retroactively marks one position as the controlled and the other as the controller (Glanville 1988, 205); thus, the concept of 'control of control' is also an epiphenomenon of the observation process and the resulting \"bindings are not a priori given data but a posteriori [observer] inferred consequences\" (Esposito 2005, 295).\n\nWith second-order cybernetics, \"observation [...] is understood as an ultimate or guiding concept that is always presupposed\" (Fuchs 2004, 11) and thus one can speak of a super-epistemitude of the concept of observation. The two basic formulas are, \"Everything that is said is said by an observer\" (Maturana 2002, 24) and, \"Everything said is said to an observer\" (Foerster 1993a, 85). All qualities and properties of things, objects, systems, etc. are thus not the qualities and properties of things, objects, and systems, but those of their description by the observer observing them (Esposito 2005, 298), more radically, \"the observer is the world\" (ibid., 296), and thus it is not the reality of the world that is relevant, but the \"reflexivity of observation\" (ibid., 293). This epistemological position ties second-order cybernetics very closely to the epistemology of constructivism (Foerster is in this sense both cyberneticist and constructivist (Foerster 1981, 1993b u. 2003))."
    },
